				\begin{document}$$ {\displaystyle \begin{array}{cc}24\hbox{-} \mathrm{hour}\ \mathrm{recall}\ (R):& R=T+{e}_R\\ {}\mathrm{FFQ}\ (Q):& Q={A}_Q+{B}_QT+q+{e}_Q\end{array}} $$\end{document}24‐hour recallR:R=T+eRFFQQ:Q=AQ+BQT+q+eQwhere T is the true (unknown) intake, e the within-person random error, and A the overall constant bias at group level, B the intake-related bias and q the person-specific bias for the FFQ. By this model, it was assumed that estimates from two replicates of the 24hRs are statistically independent and contains no intake-related bias and no person-specific bias [33].

To evaluate the performance of the FFQ versus the 24hR, linear mixed models with a random intercept for subjects were applied to account for the two replicates of the 24hRs per subject. Attenuation coefficient was estimated as the slope in the linear regression of the reference method (i.e. 24hR) on the FFQ through the following linear mixed model:2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
